.TH SIMPLE_SHELL 1 "April 2026" "Holberton School" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
simple_shell \- a simple UNIX command line interpreter
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B simple_shell
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B simple_shell
is a simple UNIX command line interpreter that reads commands from standard input and executes them.
It can operate in interactive mode (when connected to a terminal) or non-interactive mode (when reading from a pipe or file).
.PP
In interactive mode, the shell displays a prompt
.B $
and waits for the user to enter a command.
In non-interactive mode, the shell reads and executes commands without displaying a prompt.
.SH USAGE
.SS Interactive mode
.nf
$ ./simple_shell
$ /bin/ls
$ exit
.fi
.SS Non-interactive mode
.nf
$ echo "/bin/ls" | ./simple_shell
$ echo "exit" | ./simple_shell
.fi
.SH BUILTINS
.TP
.B exit
Exit the shell.
.TP
.B env
Print the current environment variables.
.SH FUNCTIONS
The following functions are used internally by
.B simple_shell:
.TP
.B fork(2)
Creates a child process to execute commands.
.TP
.B execve(2)
Executes a program in the context of the child process.
.TP
.B wait(2)
Waits for the child process to finish before returning to the prompt.
.TP
.B exit(3)
Cause normal process termination.
.TP
.B getenv(3)
Retrieves the value of the PATH environment variable to locate executables.
.TP
.B getpid(2)
Returns the process ID of the current process.
.TP
.B access(2)
Checks whether a file exists and is executable before calling execve.
.TP
.B isatty(3)
Determines whether the shell is running in interactive or non-interactive mode.
.TP
.B getline(3)
Reads a line of input from standard input.
.TP
.B strtok(3)
Tokenizes the input line into command name and arguments.
.TP
.B strcmp(3)
Compares strings, used notably to identify builtin commands.
.TP
.B free(3)
Frees dynamically allocated memory.
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
Success.
.TP
.B 1
Command not found or execution failed.
.SH RETURN VALUE
Returns the exit status of the last command executed.
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
.B PATH
A colon-separated list of directories in which the shell looks for commands.
.SH EXAMPLES
.nf
$ ./simple_shell
$ ls -la
$ /bin/echo Hello World
$ env
$ exit
.fi
.SH SEE ALSO
sh(1), bash(1), execve(2), fork(2), wait(2), getline(3), strtok(3), isatty(3)
